Folates: Folate was quantified by HPLC (Agilent 1100, Agilent Technologies, USA) consisting of a quaternary gradient pump, a thermostated autosampler (8  C) and column compartment (23  C), a fluorescence detector (ex/em 290/360 nm for reduced folates and 360/460 nm for 10-HCO‚ÄìPteGlu), a multiwavelength detector (290 nm) and Chemstation software (Rev A 10.02 [1757]). Folates were separated on an Aquasil C18 column (3 lm, 150   4.6 mm) In most foods, the folate forms H4folate, 5-CH3‚ÄìH4folate and 10- HCO‚ÄìPteGlu were quantified. The sum of these forms was expressed as folic acid in lg/100 g (Table 1). In cereals and legumes, spinach, green peppers and dried Jew‚Äôs mellow, 5-HCO‚ÄìH4folate was masked, preventing accurate quantification. The highest folate content (633 lg/100 g) was found in dried Jew‚Äôs mellow due to its low water content, followed by legumes (150 lg/100 g for chick peas) and leafy vegetables (100 lg/100 g). In other foods the folate content ranged from 10 to 90 lg/100 g. With the exception of dried Jew‚Äôs mellow, which contained more than 80% 10-HCO‚ÄìPteGlu, 5-
CH3‚ÄìH4folate was the predominant folate form in all foods, amounting to approx. 50‚Äì80% in cereals and legumes and more than 90% in vegetables. Depending on the food type, H4folate or 10-HCO‚ÄìPteGlu was the second predominant form. In general, the folate content in cereals and legumes determined by HPLC was lower than reported using the microbiological assay, which can be partly explained by lack of folate standards for all folate forms. This finding is in agreement with Ruggeri, Vahteristo, Aguzzi, Finglas, and Carnovale (1999), and Konings (1999), who reported folate contents to be 20‚Äì52% lower when determined by
HPLC. However, our data on folate content in cereals and legumes were also low compared with other HPLC data (Table 1), due to a lack of data for 5-HCO‚ÄìH4folate. According to Rychlik, Englert, Kapfer, and Kirchhoff (2007), 5-HCO‚ÄìH4folate amounts to 30% of the folate content in legumes. Pfeiffer, Rogers, and Gregory (1997) reported 29% of the folate content to be 5-HCO‚ÄìH4folate in unfortified cereal grain products. For vegetables and fruits, our data are in agreement with those reported previously using microbiological or HPLC methods.
